{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17478113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17478113"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:06+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:09:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16001"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16001","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16001"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.11,0,0.83,0.01,0.05]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8692"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64206"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8692","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8692"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16001"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49638"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"882"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4949"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7567"},{"type":"tags","id":"8130"},{"type":"tags","id":"9616"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"20799"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20802"},{"type":"contributions","id":"21052"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64206","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/64206"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA newborn presents with a midline anterior abdominal wall defect. (Image) There is herniation of bowel and other viscera through the umbilical ring. The herniated contents are covered by a thin, translucent, avascular membrane consisting of peritoneum and amnion.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Gastroschisis","Limb-body wall complex","Omphalocele","Pentalogy of Cantrell","Umbilical hernia"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis description is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003Eomphalocele\u003C/strong\u003E, where abdominal contents herniate through the umbilical ring and are covered by a protective membrane. This occurs due to failure of lateral body wall folding during weeks 3-4 of embryonic development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key distinguishing features from other conditions are:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUmbilical hernia\u003C/strong\u003E involves only a small protrusion through the umbilical ring and typically contains only fat or small bowel\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPentalogy of Cantrell\u003C/strong\u003E involves multiple midline defects including sternal, diaphragmatic, pericardial, cardiac and abdominal wall abnormalities\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastroschisis\u003C/strong\u003E typically occurs to the right of the umbilicus and the bowel is not covered by a membrane\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimb-body wall complex\u003C/strong\u003E involves multiple severe defects including limb abnormalities and thoraco-abdominal wall defects\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Omphalocele is characterised by herniation of abdominal contents through the umbilical ring covered by a membrane consisting of peritoneum and amnion.","Omphalocele occurs due to failure of lateral body wall folding during weeks 3-4 of embryonic development."],"references":["Wojcik MH, Agrawal PB. Deciphering congenital anomalies for the next generation. Cold Spring Harb Mol Case Stud. 2020 Oct 7;6(5):a005504. doi: 10.1101/mcs.a005504. PMID: 32826208; PMCID: PMC7552931","Zahouani T, Mendez MD. Omphalocele. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 30085552.","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49638"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16001"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21213"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21213","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21213"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JonHmJaEKoNAi4sQ4ViYUXGt2QW9g4.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/JonHmJaEKoNAi4sQ4ViYUXGt2QW9g4.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":502}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"49638","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/49638"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-23T08:19:41+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-23T08:20:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8692"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"64206"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"9","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/9"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc76","name":"Paediatrics","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-01-16T08:39:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Sur